Overall Design Summary – Chrome Deployment & Access Model

The Google Chrome deployment is designed using a layered group structure to ensure clear separation of responsibilities between policy enforcement, application deployment, and user access control. This approach improves consistency, reduces conflicts, and simplifies ongoing management.

⸻

1. Policy Layer – Configuration Control

The Policy Layer acts as the single source of configuration for Google Chrome.
	•	All Chrome-related settings and policies are assigned through one central group
	•	No users or devices are directly added to this layer
	•	Ensures policies are applied only where Chrome is deployed
	•	Helps maintain consistency and avoids conflicting configurations

⸻

2. Deployment Layer – Installation Management

The Deployment Layer controls how Google Chrome is delivered to users and devices.
	•	Separates deployment into:
	•	Required Installation (automatic deployment)
	•	Available Installation (user-initiated via Company Portal)
	•	These groups are nested under the Policy Layer
	•	Ensures a controlled and flexible deployment approach based on business needs

⸻

3. Access Layer – Eligibility Control

The Access Layer defines who is allowed to install Google Chrome.
	•	Uses permission-based groups to manage eligibility
	•	These groups are nested under the Available Deployment group
	•	Not directly assigned to applications or policies
	•	Provides flexible access control without impacting deployment or policy behavior

⸻

Conclusion

This layered design ensures:
	•	Clear separation between configuration, deployment, and access
	•	No overlapping assignments or conflicts
	•	Improved user experience and administrative control
	•	Simplified troubleshooting and maintenance
